.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.EPOCHNANOSECONDS" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.epochNanoseconds \-
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.epochNanoseconds
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]epochNanoseconds\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a \f[CR]BigInt\f[R]
representing the number of nanoseconds elapsed since the Unix epoch
(midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC) to this instant.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]epochNanoseconds\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
To create a new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object with the
desired new \f[CR]epochNanoseconds\f[R] value, use the
\f[CR]new Temporal.ZonedDateTime()\f[R] constructor instead.
.PP
An instant can only represent ±10\(ha8 days (about ±273,972.6 years)
around the epoch, which is ±8.64e21 nanoseconds.
Attempting to set \f[CR]epochNanoseconds\f[R] beyond this boundary
throws a \f[CR]RangeError\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using epochNanoseconds
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T12:34:56.789Z[UTC]\(dq);
console.log(zdt.epochNanoseconds); \f[I]// 1627821296789000000n\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] zdt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq1969\-08\-01T12:34:56.789Z[UTC]\(dq);
console.log(zdt2.epochNanoseconds); \f[I]// \-13173903211000000n\f[R]
.EE
.SS Creating a ZonedDateTime object from an epochNanoseconds value
You can create a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object from an
\f[CR]epochNanoseconds\f[R] value using the
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime()\f[R] constructor.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] epochNanoseconds = 1627821296789000000n;
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = \f[B]new\f[R] Temporal.ZonedDateTime(epochNanoseconds, \(dqUTC\(dq);
console.log(zdt.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-08\-01T12:34:56.789+00:00[UTC]\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
